Quin occurs perpetually in the dramatic writers, and modilies the clauses with which it is combined in so many different ways that it demands close attention. We may perhaps class the different mean- ings under three heads. Of these, two are simple and distinct, but the third is somewhat complicated.

1. Quin is employed in direct interrogations, in which case it is followed by the indicative, and is equivalent to cur nan. We may fairly regard quin here as representing qui non or qul ne. (On qut see preceding Excursus.) Quin is not unfrequently followedby the . second person of the imperative, but in this case it has in reality the iorce of a direct interrogation, as we shall point out below.
